from jhpb joseph h buehler subject the ancient canon of the roman rite the follow be a juxtaposition of part of an ancient text know a de sacramenti usually attribute to st ambrose of milan and the canon of the traditional catholic mas of the roman rite the conclusion from thi comparison be that the central part of the traditional roman canon wa already fairly well in place by sometime in the late century taken from the mas of the western rite by the right reverend dom fernand cabrol abbot of farnborough without permission excerpted from chapter vus the mas at rome from the fifth to the seventh century the paragraph at the end be from the book not me sorry about the long line joe buehler text of de sacramenti roman canon roman canon about ad ad english translation te igitur omit here memento domine communicante hanc igitur oblationem fac nobi inquit sacerdo quam oblationem tu deu in do thou o god deign to hanc oblationem ascriptam omnibu quaesumu bles what we offer and ratam rationabilem benedictam adscriptam make it approve acceptabilem quod figura ratam rationabilem effective right and est corpori et sanguini acceptabilemque facere wholly please in every jesu christus digneri ut nobi corpu et way that it may become sangui fiat dilectissimi for my good the body filius tui domini nostrus jesu and blood of thy dearly christus beloved son jesu christ my lord qui pridie quam pateretur qui pridie quam pateretur who the day before he in sancti manibu sui accepit panem in sanctum ac suffer take bread into accepit panem respexit in venerabile manu sua et hi holy and venerable caelum ad te sancte pater elevati oculus in ccelum hand and have raise omnipoten aeterne deu ad te deum patrem suum hi eye to heaven unto gratia agen benedixit omnipotentem tibi gratia thee o god hi almighty fregit fractum qua agen benedixit fregit father give thank to apostoli sui et discipuli deditque discipuli sui thee he bless it break sui tradidit dicen dicen accipite et it and give it to hi accipite et edite ex hoc manducate ex hoc omne hoc disciple say take ye omne hoc est enim corpu est enim corpu meum all and eat of thi meum quod pro multi for thi be my body confringetur similiter etiam calicem simili modo postquam in like manner when the postquam caenatum est caenatum est accipien et supper wa do take pridie quam pateretur hunc praeclarum calicem in also thi goodly chalouse accepit respexit in sanctum ac venerabile manu into hi holy and caelum ad te sancte pater sua item tibi gratia venerable hand again omnipoten aeterne deu agen benedixit deditque give thank to thee gratia agen benedixit discipuli sui dicen he bless it and give it apostoli sui et discipuli accipite et bibite ex eo to hi disciple say sui tradidit dicen omne hic est enim calix take ye all and drink of accipite et bibite ex hoc sanguini mei novus et thi for thi be the omne hic est enim sangui aeterni testamentus chalouse of my blood of the meu mysterium fidei qui pro new and eternal covenant vobi et pro multi the mystery of faith effundetur in remissionem which shall be shed for peccatorum you and for many unto the forgivenes of sin haec quotiescumque feceritis a often a you shall do in mei memoriam facieti these thing in memory of me shall you do them ergo memore gloriosissima unde et memore domine no mindful therefore o eju passioni et ab inferi servus tui sed et pleb tua lord not only of the resurrectioni in caelum sanctum ejusdem christus bless passion of the ascensioni offerimu tibi filius tui domini nostrus tam same christ thy son my hanc immaculatam hostiam beata passioni necnon et lord but also of hi hunc panem sanctum et ab inferi resurrectioni resurrection from the calicem vita aeterna sed et in caelo gloriosa dead and finally hi ascensioni offerimu gloriou ascension into praeclara majestatus tua de heaven we thy minister tui doni ac dati hostiam a also thy holy person puram hostiam sanctam offer unto thy supreme hostiam immaculatam panem majesty of the gift sanctum vita aeterna et bestow upon u the calicem saluti perpetua pure victim the holy victim the all-perfect victim the holy bread of life eternal and the chalouse of unending salvation et petimu et precamur ut supra qua propitio ac and thi do thou deign to hanc oblationem suscipia in sereno vultu respicere regard with graciou and sublimi altarus tuo per manu digneri et acceptum habere kindly attention and hold angelorum tuorum sicut sicutus acceptum habere acceptable a thou didst suscipere dignatu e munera dignatu e munera puerus tui deign to accept the puerus tui justus abel et justus abel et sacrificium offer of abel thy sacrificium patriarcha patriarcha nostrus abraha just servant and the nostrus abraha et quod tibi et quod tibi obtulit summu sacrifice of abraham my obtulit summu sacerdo sacerdo tuu melchisedech patriarch and that which melchisedech sanctum sacrificium thy chief priest immaculatam hostiam melchisedech offer unto thee a holy sacrifice and a spotles victim supplice te rogamu most humbly we implore omnipoten deu jube haec thee almighty god bid perferrus per manu sanctus these offer to be angeli tui in sublime altare bring by the hand of tuum in conspectu divina thy holy angel unto thy majestati tua etc altar above before the face of thy divine majesty etc there be no doubt that we have here two edition of the same text and a that of de sacramenti be localise in upper italy and date about the year it be the most ancient witnes we posse a to the principal part of the roman canon which only appear in the sacramentary some time after the seventh century the question a to whether the roman canon be not older even than that of de sacramenti be discuss by liturgiologist mgr batiffol be of thi opinion but we on the contrary think that the former bear trace of closer composition of a more carefully guard orthodoxy and that consequently it be a text correct from de sacramenti we shall see in study the list of name in the memento of the live and that of the dead that mgr batiffol argue with good reason that he can date these fragment from the pontificate of symmachu we thu have the state of the roman mas or at least of the chief part of the canon at the begin of the fourth century 